du, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Haydock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Haddock   1 and 2.","Americanized form of Czech or Polish   Hejduk  , Polish, Slovak, Rusyn (from Slovakia and Poland), or Czech   Hajduk  , and of their Hungarian cognate <b>Hajdók</b>. Compare   Hydock  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Haddock","meanings":["English:","variant of the Lancashire surname   Haydock  , a habitational name from a place so called near Liverpool, which is probably named from Welsh <i>heiddog</i> ‘characterized by barley’.","from the Middle English personal name <i>Addoc</i>, a pet form of Old English <i>Æddi</i> (itself perhaps derived from one of the names in <i>ēad</i> ‘wealth, prosperity’), with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]}]},{"name":"Alfredus","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: variant of   Alfred   with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Alfred","meanings":["From an Old English name derived from <i>ælf</i> ‘elf, supernatural being’ + <i>ræd</i> ‘counsel’. It was a relatively common name before the Norman Conquest of Britain, being borne most notably by  Alfred the Great  (  849–899 ), King of Wessex. After the Conquest it was adopted by the Normans in a variety of more or less radically altered forms (  see  Avery  ). In some regions the forms <i>Alvery</i> and <i>Avery</i> never fell entirely out 